    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-06-01T18:15:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-06-01T18:15:00-05:00" n="807"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d807">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense (M) Chile/471b: Airgram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Chile</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bowers</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-06-01T19:15:00-04:00"
                            >June 1, 1943—7:15 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>A–862. With respect to the control of exports of refined and semimanufactured
                    copper from Chile, the Department desires to bring to the Embassy’s attention a
                    paragraph in despatch no. 327 of May 17, 1943, from Buenos Aires,<note n="9"
                        xml:id="d807fn9">Despatch not printed.</note> reading as follows: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="italic">“Copper and Copper products</hi>—Heavy imports of
                            copper and copper products from Chile continue despite the fact that
                            stocks in the Argentine are believed to approach minimum requirements
                            for the rest of 1943. An appreciable portion of these stocks are held by
                            the black-listed firm Sema,<note n="10" xml:id="d807fn10">Sociedad
                                Electro Metalurgico Argentina.</note> which firm has succeeded in
                            augmenting its stocks during recent months. Copper is rapidly becoming
                            an allservice metal in the Argentine economy, replacing for many uses
                            other <pb facs="0855" n="843" xml:id="pg_843"/> metals. So abundant are
                            supplies that manufacturers who formerly only worked with used bronze or
                            copper now purchase the new product.[”]</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
